\section{Motivation}
%In order to familiarize the AA Ocean Capstone team with Seaglider piloting and data output, a tank test will be carried out. This will allow the capstone team to determine how to best design their digital twin deliverable to intake the Seaglider outputs.

Field testing will confirm the digital twin's data outputs, as well as determine the percent effect of variable wing and rudder damage on those data outputs. This will both finalize critical system and functional requirement requirement data needs, as well as begin the characterization of wing and rudder damage in the fault database.
%how far are we going
\section{Scope} %Holland pls double check this
The intention is for this test to occur in the first week of UW Spring Quarter 2026, date and time to be finalized at the UW Student Seaglider Center's (SSC) discretion. It is intended to integrate with SSC operations and minimize the impact on SSC scheduling. As such, the field test will resemble their normal operational procedures with the only addition being the enacted wing and rudder fault cases.


%what is the testing enviornment like/safety
\section{Test Environment/Safety/}%not sure what to call this
\subsection{Test Environment}
The field test will occur through deploying the Seaglider off the boat's launch cradle and into the open Puget Sound, where the Seaglider will dive as it would during a normal operation. Up until deployment, all procedures, precautions, and scheduling will be under the jurisdiction of the SSC.  
\subsection{Safety}
Due to the nature of open ocean boat travel and Seaglider mission deployment, any capstone member selected to overview the field test must acquire the proper training under the SSC's discretion. All UW School of Oceanography and SSC instructions will be followed in order to prevent risk of injury or death. 
